SIMPLE: luscious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Luscious
<hw>Lus"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Prob. for
<ets>lustious</ets>, fr. <ets>lusty</ets>, or perh. a corruption of
<ets>luxurious</ets>. Cf. <er>Lush</er>, <er>Lusty</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Sweet; delicious; very grateful to the taste;
toothsome; excessively sweet or rich.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And raisins keep their <qex>luscious</qex>, native taste.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Cloying; fulsome.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had a tedious, <qex>luscious</qex> way of talking.</q>
<rj><qau>Jeffrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Gratifying a depraved sense; obscene.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Steele.</au></rj></p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Lus"cious*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Lus"cious*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lusern</ent>⟦br⟧
